00:45.820 --> 00:54.020
This is David Carson. And David Crews. Over the next several programs, we are
going to be talking with and about author and editor Joe Haldeman. Although he

00:54.020 --> 01:01.940
appeared in print for the first time in 1969 with a short story in the science
fiction magazine Galaxy, Haldeman gained tremendous popularity when he came out

01:01.940 --> 01:11.180
with his multi-award winning novel, The Forever War. The novel was serialized in
astounding science fiction, starting in 1972, then released as a book in 1974.

01:11.800 --> 01:19.800
The Forever War is similar to Robert Heinlein's book, Starship Troopers, in that
both have intergalactic war, powered body armor, and highly advanced weapons as

01:19.800 --> 01:27.860
common elements. Differences between the books show up in the way the authors
treat war. Heinlein's conflict was sort of a John Wayne-style battle with the

01:27.860 --> 01:35.580
bad guys, whereas Haldeman's dealt with the emotions and reactions of his
characters to the war they fought. We asked Haldeman if the resemblance was

01:35.580 --> 01:47.880
intentional. Well, there was no rough intention on my part. In fact, I didn't
realize until I was about 70 or 80 pages into the book that many of the details

01:47.880 --> 01:57.000
were similar to Starship Troopers. Somebody else pointed that out when he read
the manuscript. I wasn't doing an answer to Heinlein's book. I thought

01:57.000 --> 02:02.980
Heinlein's book was admirable in many ways, even though we have diametrically
opposed philosophies.

02:06.900 --> 02:20.820
No, if there's any relation to any book, it is to my own first novel, War Year,
because it's an expansion into a science-fiction universe. of the notions that I

02:20.820 --> 02:24.900
was trying to express in mainstream novel.

02:43.680 --> 02:49.860
Haldeman has a background in physics and astronomy and told us about how he uses
his hard science background in his work.

03:19.380 --> 03:27.160
by a real scientist's standards, it's still enough to convince me. So it's
fulfilled its function.

03:34.660 --> 03:42.180
In the Forever War, the soldiers experience time dilation when they travel to
and from the war zone. That means that due to the tremendous velocity of their

03:42.180 --> 03:50.100
spaceships, dozens of years have passed on Earth, while only a few months have
passed for the soldiers on the spaceships. Haldeman told us how he used hard

03:50.100 --> 04:02.700
science to evoke some of the feeling the soldiers have. It goes deeper than just
description, the time dilation in the forever war. Though it's scientifically

04:02.700 --> 04:15.100
accurate, its main function is metaphorical, and that is to demonstrate how the
soldiers who fight a war become isolated from the culture that they're supposed

04:15.100 --> 04:28.140
to be protecting. using a science fictional device to exaggerate something that
happens to every soldier. I remember when I came back from Vietnam. I was

04:28.140 --> 04:41.380
suddenly plunged into what was an alien culture, even though I'd only been a
soldier for two years. A lot of things had changed. It's not a great thing to

04:41.380 --> 04:44.840
come back. There were no victory parades, that sort of thing.

04:57.820 --> 05:00.620
Join us next time when we continue our interview with Joe Haldeman.

