06:40.320 --> 06:48.160
This is David Carson. And David Crews. Today we'll be continuing our interview
with author Joe Haldeman. It was mentioned in the previous program that Haldeman

06:48.160 --> 06:56.380
served in Vietnam and uses that experience in some of his stories. For instance,
in one of his stories he tells of a soldier who is severely hurt by a laser

06:56.380 --> 07:07.800
mine. We asked Haldeman if that was drawn from his own experiences. I was
wounded pretty severely in Vietnam. I was hospitalized for six months. And it

07:07.800 --> 07:18.900
was a booby trap. I didn't set it off. Somebody else did, but it was a pretty
big one. I had over 200 separate wounds, but managed to come out of it all right

07:18.900 --> 07:31.960
after a few months of physical therapy. So it's, yeah, I draw on that
experience. The one you're talking about is a mind of his own, but I think I've

07:31.960 --> 07:42.200
got other short stories like The Private War of Private Jacob of the draw on
that memory. We wondered if he was exercising demons by writing about that

07:42.200 --> 07:57.940
experience. I don't know whether I am or not. I think I'm just using available
material. I don't think the demon is too easily exercised by fiction. We asked

07:57.940 --> 08:11.440
if being in Vietnam had any other effects on his writing. Being in the army had
an important on my writing aside from war, because I met a whole new class of

08:11.440 --> 08:25.740
people. That is, all of my friends, while I was growing up, tended to be white
middle-class upper-middle-class kids and their successors, white middle-class

08:25.740 --> 08:38.480
upper-class scientists so forth. It was just a mundane revelation to find that
people who came from different backgrounds still had an awful lot in common with

08:38.480 --> 08:52.380
me. Most of the guys in my combat outfit were urban black high school or junior
high school dropouts. And I got along quite well. Haldeman has written two

08:52.380 --> 09:00.300
novels and edited one anthology, all dealing with war, but by no means should
you consider him just a writer of war stories. That's right. He writes about

09:00.300 --> 09:08.440
what happens to people who are placed in that type of violent situation. He
seems to be exploring what makes his characters tick more than the situation

09:08.440 --> 09:18.260
surrounding the characters. One of the themes in his work is man or mankind
being changed when facing conflict. We asked Haldeman to respond to that. I

09:18.260 --> 09:29.780
think it's obvious that confronting death on a daily basis changes people, and
sometimes radically for the worse, and that people who are totally dehumanized

09:29.780 --> 09:41.900
by war. but speaking racially, I don't think you could make such a broad
statement. What's behind some of the things I'm writing is the hope that human

09:41.900 --> 09:54.540
nature eventually may improve to the point where we won't have wars and find
other ways to settle our differences. In his novel, All My Sins Remembered, the

09:54.540 --> 10:01.580
main character is red-taped and shuffled into doing something that he is
diametrically opposed to. When he rebels against the situation, he is

10:01.580 --> 10:14.340
terminated. The story is about a bureaucracy that totally takes over a man's
identity and he doesn't really exist except as a tool for that bureaucracy. When

10:14.340 --> 10:26.740
he becomes an efficient tool, he's scrapped. The main character ends up being a
spy for the government and carrying out covert operations for them. And he does

10:26.740 --> 10:36.800
them more or less against his will That is to say, through very advanced
techniques of conditioning, he's turned into a thoroughly different person. He

10:36.800 --> 10:49.640
was a Buddhist, a pacifist when he started out. They did not get the job he
signed up for. They twisted him around into being a killing machine. If all this

10:49.640 --> 10:55.800
makes Haldeman sound like a pessimist, well, he's not that either. Join us next
time when we find out more about Joe Haldeman.

