12:29.840 --> 12:39.060
This is David Carson and David Crews. Today we continue our interview with author
Joe Haldeman. So far in our conversation with Haldeman, we've discussed how he

12:39.060 --> 12:47.260
used his experiences in Vietnam in his writing and some of his early works. Now
we're going to look at his writing style in two particular stories, a short

12:47.260 --> 12:56.040
story to Howard Hughes' A Modest Proposal and a novel, Mindbridge. Haldeman
tells these stories by using narratives by the main characters in the stories,

12:56.320 --> 13:05.140
reports by them and others, portions of books written long after the time set in
the story, and other non-standard writing techniques. We asked him if he got the

13:05.140 --> 13:17.160
ideas for this type of style when he was attending the Iowa Writers' Conference.
Oh, not really. The connection is with John dos Passos, actually. I read the USA

13:17.160 --> 13:26.760
trilogy some years before I wrote Mind Bridge. and really was impressed by the
way it worked and thought it would work really well in science fiction. So I

13:26.760 --> 13:37.860
tried it out in a rather long short story to Howard Hughes, A Modest Proposal,
and it looked like it would work, so I went ahead and applied it to MindBridge.

13:39.480 --> 13:48.840
I did do most of that book while I was studying at Iowa, and that's why I did
the occasion. The authors at the Iowa Writers Conference were, for the most

13:48.840 --> 13:56.940
part, not science fiction writers. We asked Haldemann about their reaction to
his being a science fiction author. Well, they were a little apprehensive about

13:56.940 --> 14:05.860
it. See, they didn't know I was a science fiction writer when I joined the
workshop. So I joined on the basis of my first novel, which was not science

14:05.860 --> 14:18.200
fiction. And some of them were outwardly hostile towards science fiction, such
as Stanley Elkham. Others were anywhere between apprehensive and slightly

14:18.200 --> 14:31.280
sympathetic. Stephen Becker, one of them, had actually had a few pieces in the
magazine Fantasy and Science Fiction. In general, though, they thinly disguised

14:31.280 --> 14:43.100
the attitude that this stuff was just commercial fiction and therefore beneath
contempt. That's an attitude I've never understood. some of the world's finest

14:43.100 --> 14:54.480
literature is science fiction. We asked Haldeman what he thought about that type
of attitude. But the field is judged by its worst, not by its best. And people

14:54.480 --> 15:05.280
like that think of science fiction, they think in terms of grade B movies and
lousy television. They've never read much of the best of the field.

15:11.700 --> 15:19.360
Using science fiction, it's possible to consider various aspects of mankind's
future, and science fiction is the only literary form to speculate about the

15:19.360 --> 15:29.000
future. We asked Haldeman if he thought that mankind might be radically
different in the future. I think it's quite possible, even, say, within the span

15:29.000 --> 15:45.760
of a century. So many of the things that determine human nature are things that
can be mitigated by technology, such as the problem of dying so soon, that it's

15:45.760 --> 15:56.260
possible that we'll, in a couple of generations, be able to live a century, two
centuries, maybe a thousand years, maybe as long as we care to. That will

15:56.260 --> 16:01.220
radically change human nature because it will take the pressure off of
individuals.

16:04.320 --> 16:19.920
there are other less tango notions it's possible that sciences and communication
will grow into a kind of sophisticated mind control where it will be difficult

16:19.920 --> 16:30.700
for the individual to know exactly what is his idea and what has been induced by
his own society sort of a sophisticated lifelong brainwashing It doesn't seem

16:30.700 --> 16:41.460
too unlikely, if you can argue that it's set now. Join us next time when we wrap
up our interview with Joe Haldeman and find out how he got involved with Star

16:41.460 --> 16:41.780
Trek.

