24:05.200 --> 24:13.960
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. What makes science fiction a separate
branch of literature? Why is it distinct from so-called mainstream or regular

24:13.960 --> 24:23.320
literature? And should it be? We asked science fiction author Jack Chalker if
mainstream writing and science fiction are essentially different. No, they

24:23.320 --> 24:36.040
aren't. There's no way that you can. It is rather odd, though. It's an
ambivalent answer. Clifford Sumac once said that there is some difference

24:36.040 --> 24:47.780
because science fiction writers you will find writing every other form of
literature mysteries, romances, mainstream war novels you name it but when

24:47.780 --> 24:58.400
people who write other things try and write science fiction they usually fall
flat on their face but there really isn't that much difference an awful lot of

24:58.400 --> 25:08.500
people write an awful lot of stuff And a great deal of it is science fiction and
fantasy, whether or not it's categorized that way.

25:11.540 --> 25:22.380
The ghettoization of it is strictly a marketing thing. Another science fiction
figure, Frederik Pohl, who's been an editor, agent, and writer, and knows the

25:22.380 --> 25:31.440
field, as few other people do, agrees that it's the publishing industry that
keeps science fiction separate. well the publishing industry is responsible for

25:31.440 --> 25:40.360
that and in some ways it's a bad thing a lot of people in this world like to
read books but are prejudiced against anything that has the word science fiction

25:40.360 --> 25:52.320
on it as i think it's um i've forgotten the person who wrote the poem a little
poem about it which says something like if it's science fiction i don't like it

25:52.320 --> 25:59.240
and if i it, it can't possibly be science fiction, because there are a great
many science fiction novels that everybody loves. They just don't admit they're

25:59.240 --> 26:01.880
science fiction. Brave New World in 1984.

26:04.480 --> 26:17.680
But I don't mind that. I'm perfectly willing to have the word science fiction on
the cover of any book I write. It's only a sort of geographical designation.

26:17.800 --> 26:27.780
It's the name they put on the shelves where the books appear that the people who
like to write, read my books are going to go. Jack Williamson has been writing

26:27.780 --> 26:36.660
science fiction for well over half a century, and he shares Pohl's pride in being
recognized not just as a writer, but as a science fiction writer. I'm not

26:36.660 --> 26:38.180
enthusiastic about

26:40.700 --> 26:52.140
consolidating mainstream literature and science fiction, but I also remember
that there was a time when science fiction wasn't walled off in a category by

26:52.140 --> 27:02.180
itself and I don't think there's any reason it should be when Wells was
publishing his stories they were just novels or romances or whatever and the

27:02.180 --> 27:15.660
science fiction was in a sort of ghetto quote ghetto for a generation I think
this was partly due to the fact that it was published in pulp magazines and

27:15.660 --> 27:28.500
people looked down on the pulps I think we're sort of getting over that, but
it's still a category, a publisher's category, like westerns or gothics or love

27:28.500 --> 27:43.280
romances or whatever. And that means that if Don Wilhelm or Judy-Lynn Del Rey or
someone else packages a book in a recognizable science fiction package, it'll

27:43.280 --> 27:54.820
sell enough copies to make a profit. But it's a sort of limited profit because
it is shelled in the science fiction recs and the stands, and the general public

27:54.820 --> 28:07.540
doesn't see it. So people who get to be best sellers successful—people like
Vonnegut and so

28:07.540 --> 28:17.480
forth—tend to want to get the science fiction label off their stories when they
begin to sell enough copies. But I've never reached that stage myself. I'm proud

28:17.480 --> 28:19.100
to have mine called science fiction.

